
##### shell script####

Shebang ‚Äì telling the system how to run the script

#!/bin/bash
This line tells Linux:
 ‚ÄúRun this script using the Bash shell.

####Variables ‚Äì taking input from the command line####

P1=$1
P2=$2
$1 ‚Üí first argument passed to the script

$2 ‚Üí second argument passed to the script

Example:

./script.sh devops partice
P1 = devops

P2 =  partice


#####Simple conversation using variables####

echo ${P1} : hello how are you ${P2}
echo ${P2} : i am good $P1, how about you
This just prints a friendly conversation using the values passed from the command line.


###Special shell variables###

echo all args passed to script : $@
echo number of args passed to script : $#
echo current user : $USER
echo current user home directory path : $HOME
echo process id of script : $$
echo recent background process id : $!


What these mean in real life:==============>>>

Special shell variable

$@ ‚Üí all arguments given to the script

$# ‚Üí total number of arguments

$USER ‚Üí current logged-in user

$HOME ‚Üí home directory path

$0 shows the name of the script itself

$$ ‚Üí process ID of the running script

$!  ‚Üí gives the PID of the last background process

$? checks whether the previous command succeeded or failed


Background process example:

sleep 20 &
echo recent background process id : $!
sleep 20 & runs in the background

$! gives the PID of the last background process



##Script name##

echo script name : $0
$0 shows the name of the script itself

Taking input from the user

read -p "" USER_NAME
echo user name is : $USER_NAME
Reads username from the keyboard

Stores it in USER_NAME

Reading password (hidden input üîê)
read -sp "" PASSWORD
-s hides the password while typing

Used for secure input


####Measuring execution time###

START_TIME=$(date +%s)
sleep 10
END_TIME=$(date +%s)
RUN_TIME=$(($END_TIME-$START_TIME))
What‚Äôs happening:

Script notes start time

Waits for 10 seconds

Notes end time

Calculates how long the script ran

 Data types ‚Äì integers and strings
x=10
y= Banu
sum=$(($x+$y))
x is a number

y is a string
‚ö†Ô∏è Bash cannot add numbers and strings, so this will cause an error or unexpected result.


####Arrays in shell###

FRUITS=("mango" "watermleon" "grapes")
This creates a list (array) of fruits

echo ${FRUITS[@]}
Prints all fruits

echo ${FRUITS[0]}
Access elements by index (starting from 0)


######Conditions (if‚Äìelif‚Äìelse)#####

NUMBER=500
if [ $NUMBER -gt 500 ]; then
Checks if the number is greater than 500

elif [ $NUMBER -eq 500 ]; then
Checks if the number is exactly 500

else
Runs if none of the above conditions are true


########Root user check ########

USERID=$(id -u)
id -u returns 0 for root user

if [ $USERID -ne 0 ]; then
	echo "please run with root user access"
	exit 1
fi

If not root ‚Üí stop the script

Installing software (nginx example)

dnf install nginx -y
Installs nginx automatically

if [ $? -ne 0 ]; then
$? checks whether the previous command succeeded or failed

If installation fails ‚Üí show error
If successful ‚Üí show success message ‚úÖ



#####Easy takeaway#####
This script demonstrates:

Passing arguments

Using special shell variables

Reading user input

Background processes

Arrays

Conditions

Execution time calculation

Root permission checks

Package installation